# 4. Development Rules

- **No feature skipping:** No phase's scope is partially implemented and left incomplete while a later phase begins.
- **No duplicate code:** Consistent with Phase 0.3's Development Standards — shared logic is always extracted and reused, never copy-pasted across phases.
- **No redesigning approved UI:** Every phase that touches the frontend must conform exactly to Phase 0.4's design system and the approved prototype — no phase introduces new visual patterns without an explicit, documented amendment.
- **Documentation before implementation:** Every phase's detailed spec document (per the template in Section 3) is written and committed before that phase's implementation commits begin, per Phase 0.3's Documentation Standards.
- **Testing before completion:** No phase is marked complete without satisfying its own Completion Criteria and, from Phase 20 onward, the broader Testing Strategy in Section 7.

---

# 5. Git Workflow

- **Branch naming:** `phase-<number>-<short-description>` (e.g. `phase-8-prediction-engine`), consistent with the convention already locked in the README and Phase 0.3.
- **Commit naming:** Conventional commit prefixes (`feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `style:`, `docs:`, `chore:`), consistent with Phase 0.3's Git Standards.
- **Merge policy:** A phase's branch is merged into `main` only once it satisfies its Completion Criteria; `main` always represents a working, production-ready state of the project.
- **Version tagging:** Each completed phase is tagged (e.g. `phase-8-complete`), providing a clear, navigable history of the project's incremental growth.
- **Milestone rules:** Major roadmap milestones — completion of the foundational documentation set (Phase 0.7, this document), completion of the core prediction loop (Phases 1–11), and Production Launch (Phase 22) — are tagged as named milestones in addition to per-phase tags.

---

# 6. Quality Standards

- **Frontend quality:** Every UI element matches Phase 0.4's design system exactly; components follow Phase 0.3's coding standards (strict typing, feature-first organization, no duplicated components).
- **Backend quality:** Every endpoint matches its Phase 0.6 contract exactly; business logic enforces the validation and security rules defined there without exception.
- **Database quality:** Every schema element matches Phase 0.5's entity model exactly, including ownership, relationship, and deletion-rule fidelity.
- **API quality:** Consistent request/response/error shapes across every module, per Phase 0.6 — no module introduces a one-off convention.
- **Documentation quality:** Every phase's spec follows the template in Section 3; this roadmap and all Phase 0.x documents remain internally consistent as new phases are added.
- **Code review philosophy:** Even as a solo developer, each phase's implementation is reviewed against its own written spec and against this roadmap's Development Rules (Section 4) before being considered complete — the written spec serves as the review checklist.

---

# 7. Testing Strategy

- **Unit testing philosophy:** Core business logic — Points ledger calculations, prediction settlement, leaderboard computation — is covered by unit tests that verify correctness independent of the full system, prioritized over exhaustive UI-level unit testing.
- **Integration testing philosophy:** Critical cross-module flows (placing a prediction and verifying the resulting Points Transaction and Portfolio update together) are covered by integration tests that exercise real module boundaries, per Phase 0.6's contracts.
- **Manual testing:** Every phase undergoes a manual walkthrough against its own Completion Criteria before being marked complete; a full manual regression pass across all Core Features occurs during Phase 20.
- **Regression testing:** As new phases are added, previously completed phases are periodically re-verified (informally per-phase, formally during Phase 20) to catch any unintended breakage introduced by later work.
- **Bug fixing workflow:** Bugs discovered during or after a phase are fixed under a `fix:` commit (per Section 5) within the current phase if found before completion, or as a dedicated fix branch/commit against `main` if found afterward — bugs are never silently patched without a corresponding commit trail.

---

# 8. Deployment Roadmap

- **Development:** Local development environment, using the technology stack from Phase 0.3, throughout Phases 1–20.
- **Staging:** A production-equivalent environment (Vercel for frontend, Railway for backend, Supabase for database/auth/storage) stood up in Phase 21, used to validate the platform before real users are exposed to it.
- **Production:** The live environment, served under the project's custom domain via Cloudflare DNS (per Phase 0.3), stood up as the final step of Phase 21 and opened to the public in Phase 22.
- **Rollback philosophy:** Every production deployment is expected to be reversible — the deployment process (finalized in detail during Phase 21) must support returning to the previous known-good state if a release introduces a critical issue.
- **Environment separation:** Development, staging, and production use entirely separate databases, environment variables, and credentials at all times — no environment ever shares live data or secrets with another, consistent with Phase 0.3's Security Standards.

---

# 9. Release Strategy

- **Alpha:** Internal-only milestone, reached once the core prediction loop (Phases 1–11) is functionally complete, used solely for the developer's own end-to-end validation.
- **Beta:** A limited, controlled release reached once Phases 12–17 are complete, allowing real (but limited/invited) usage to surface issues before full hardening.
- **Release Candidate:** The build produced at the end of Phase 20 (Testing) — considered launch-ready pending final Security Hardening (Phase 19, sequenced appropriately) and Deployment (Phase 21) validation.
- **Production Release:** The result of Phase 22 — the platform is live and publicly accessible.
- **Hotfix Releases:** Post-launch, urgent fixes bypass the standard phase sequence only to the extent needed to resolve the specific issue, are branched, committed, and tagged following the same Git Workflow (Section 5), and are documented after the fact in the changelog (per Phase 0.3's Documentation Standards).

---

# 10. Maintenance Philosophy

- **Bug fixes:** Handled per the Bug Fixing Workflow in Section 7, prioritized by severity and user impact.
- **Feature updates:** Post-launch features are treated as new, fully-specified phases (following the Section 3 template) rather than ad hoc additions — the phase-based discipline continues after Production Launch, not just before it.
- **Documentation updates:** Every maintenance change that affects architecture, data model, API contracts, or design is reflected back into the relevant Phase 0.x document as a formal, documented amendment, keeping the foundational documents perpetually accurate.
- **Performance monitoring:** Ongoing observation of the benchmarks established in Phase 18, with regressions treated as bugs under the standard workflow.
- **Future scalability:** Growth-driven changes (e.g. new categories, increased user volume) are evaluated against the scalability philosophy already established in Phases 0.2 and 0.5 before any structural change is made.

---

# 11. Risk Management

- **Scope creep:** Mitigated by the Development Rules (Section 4) and the strict phase-by-phase discipline established in the README and reinforced throughout every Phase 0.x document.
- **Breaking changes:** Mitigated by the API versioning philosophy (Phase 0.6) and the requirement that `main` always remains in a working state (Section 5).
- **Performance issues:** Addressed proactively through Phase 18 and the performance philosophies already embedded in Phases 0.3 and 0.6, rather than deferred entirely to a single late-stage effort.
- **Security issues:** Addressed proactively through the security standards already embedded in Phases 0.3 and 0.6, with a dedicated verification pass in Phase 19.
- **Database migrations:** Managed carefully given the permanence/immutability rules in Phase 0.5 — schema changes that could affect historical data (Points Transactions, Prediction History) require explicit, documented review before being applied, even after Production Launch.
- **API compatibility:** Managed through the versioning and backward-compatibility rules in Phase 0.6 — no endpoint contract is broken without a new API version.

---

# 12. Success Criteria

The platform is considered officially production-ready when all of the following are true:

1. All functional phases (1–17) are complete, each having met its own Completion Criteria.
2. Performance Optimization (Phase 18) has met its established benchmarks.
3. Security Hardening (Phase 19) has found no remaining known high-severity issues.
4. Testing (Phase 20) shows critical-path automated test coverage and a clean manual regression pass.
5. Deployment (Phase 21) has produced a validated staging environment and a correctly configured production environment (custom domain, DNS, environment separation).
6. The platform, end to end, faithfully reflects the approved prototype's design (Phase 0.4), the data model (Phase 0.5), and the API contracts (Phase 0.6), with no unresolved contradictions between documentation and implementation.
7. The Points-only rule (README, and every subsequent document) holds with zero exceptions anywhere in the implemented system.

